<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="325" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="4.[677,1211,643,720]" pageId="4" pageNumber="325">GEOLOGIC AND GEOGRAPHIC DISTRIBUTION. — Early Devonian (Early Lochkovian) of the Midland Valley of Scotland.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[675,1211,743,979]" pageId="4" pageNumber="325">REVISED DIAGNOSIS. — Medium-sized, fusiform fish with maximum length to depth ratio5:1; jaws formed of calcified cartilage; slender closeset branchiostegal plates; fin spines relatively slender and straight with smooth longitudinal ridges separated by deep smooth grooves; four or five pairs of prepelvic spines; posterior dorsal fin spine longer than anterior dorsal fin spine; scales ornamented with subparallel rounded ridges leading back from the anterior edge of the crown, with a slightly convex base.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="5" lastPageNumber="326" pageId="4" pageNumber="325" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="4.[675,1212,1008,1700]" box="[677,777,1008,1034]" pageId="4" pageNumber="325">REMARKS</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="4.[675,1212,1008,1700]" pageId="4" pageNumber="325">
When 
<bibRefCitation author="POWRIE J." box="[751,905,1039,1066]" pageId="4" pageNumber="325" pagination="413 - 429" refId="ref14777" refString="POWRIE J. 1864. - On the fossiliferous rocks of Forfarshire and their contents. Quarterly Journal of the Geological Society of London 47: 413 - 429." type="journal article" year="1864">Powrie (1864)</bibRefCitation>
first described 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Powrie" authorityYear="1864" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="4" pageNumber="325" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macnicoli">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="325">Euthacanthus macnicoli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
he had only one complete specimen at his disposal, the 
<typeStatus box="[865,961,1103,1129]" pageId="4" pageNumber="325">holotype</typeStatus>
NMS G.1891.92.231 from Turin Hill (although he mentioned no locality at this time). 
<bibRefCitation author="POWRIE J." box="[856,1010,1166,1193]" pageId="4" pageNumber="325" pagination="413 - 429" refId="ref14777" refString="POWRIE J. 1864. - On the fossiliferous rocks of Forfarshire and their contents. Quarterly Journal of the Geological Society of London 47: 413 - 429." type="journal article" year="1864">Powrie (1864)</bibRefCitation>
also stated that he had disarticulated remains which indicated that the species grew quite large and that some of the remains showed that another species was present. Later, 
<bibRefCitation author="POWRIE J." box="[743,895,1293,1319]" pageId="4" pageNumber="325" pagination="284 - 301" refId="ref14807" refString="POWRIE J. 1870. - On the earliest known vestiges of vertebrate life; being a description of the fish remains of the Old Red Sandstone rocks of Forfarshire. Transactions of the Edinburgh Geological Society 1: 284 - 301." type="journal article" year="1870">Powrie (1870)</bibRefCitation>
stated that his first specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Powrie" authorityYear="1864" box="[708,844,1325,1351]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="4" pageNumber="325" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macnicoli">
<emphasis box="[708,724,1325,1350]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="325">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[741,844,1325,1351]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="325">macnicoli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
came from Farnell and Tealing, though no remains from these localities in his collection can be said with confidence to belong to this species. Articulated 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Powrie" authorityYear="1864" box="[948,1091,1420,1446]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="4" pageNumber="325" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[948,1091,1420,1446]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="325">Euthacanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
specimens from these localities are now assigned to 
<taxonomicName authority="(Newman et al. 2011)" baseAuthorityName="Newman" baseAuthorityYear="2011" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="4" pageNumber="325" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gracilis">
<emphasis box="[1111,1127,1452,1477]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="325">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[1138,1209,1451,1477]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="325">gracilis</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="NEWMAN M. J. &amp; DAVIDSON R. G. &amp; DEN BLAAUWEN J. L. &amp; BURROW C. J." box="[684,902,1483,1509]" pageId="4" pageNumber="325" pagination="101 - 111" refId="ref14554" refString="NEWMAN M. J., DAVIDSON R. G., DEN BLAAUWEN J. L. &amp; BURROW C. J. 2011. - The Early Devonian acanthodian Euthacanthus gracilis from the Midland Valley of Scotland. Scottish Journal of Geology 47: 101 - 111." type="journal article" year="2011">
Newman 
<emphasis box="[789,838,1483,1509]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="325">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. 
<bibRefCitation author="POWRIE J." box="[919,1070,1483,1510]" pageId="4" pageNumber="325" pagination="413 - 429" refId="ref14777" refString="POWRIE J. 1864. - On the fossiliferous rocks of Forfarshire and their contents. Quarterly Journal of the Geological Society of London 47: 413 - 429." type="journal article" year="1864">Powrie (1864)</bibRefCitation>
believed that all the fish beds at the different localities constituted one continuous lake deposit, hence he assigned any disarticulated remains to his first named species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Powrie" authorityYear="1864" box="[678,815,1610,1636]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="4" pageNumber="325" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macnicoli">
<emphasis box="[678,693,1611,1636]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="325">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[710,815,1610,1636]" italics="true" pageId="4" pageNumber="325">macnicoli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, 
<bibRefCitation author="ARMSTRONG M. &amp; PATERSON I. B." pageId="4" pageNumber="325" pagination="1 - 23" refId="ref13045" refString="ARMSTRONG M. &amp; PATERSON I. B. 1970. - The Lower Old Red Sandstone of the Strathmore Region. Institute of Geological Sciences Report 70 / 12: 1 - 23." type="journal article" year="1970">Armstrong &amp; Paterson (1970)</bibRefCitation>
demonstrated that the fossil fish localities are at various stratigraphic horizons.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[111,649,216,1700]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">
<bibRefCitation author="POWRIE J." box="[136,287,216,242]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" pagination="284 - 301" refId="ref14807" refString="POWRIE J. 1870. - On the earliest known vestiges of vertebrate life; being a description of the fish remains of the Old Red Sandstone rocks of Forfarshire. Transactions of the Edinburgh Geological Society 1: 284 - 301." type="journal article" year="1870">Powrie (1870)</bibRefCitation>
stated that he had two reasonably complete specimens of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Powrie" authorityYear="1864" box="[361,489,247,274]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macnicoli">
<emphasis box="[361,377,248,273]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[392,489,247,273]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">macnicoli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and that these came from Turin Hill. In the same publication, he raised another species, 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Powrie" authorityYear="1870" box="[352,568,311,337]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="grandis">
<emphasis box="[352,568,311,337]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">Euthacanthus grandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, which he said only occurred at Turin Hill. 
<bibRefCitation author="POWRIE J." box="[495,647,342,369]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" pagination="284 - 301" refId="ref14807" refString="POWRIE J. 1870. - On the earliest known vestiges of vertebrate life; being a description of the fish remains of the Old Red Sandstone rocks of Forfarshire. Transactions of the Edinburgh Geological Society 1: 284 - 301." type="journal article" year="1870">Powrie (1870)</bibRefCitation>
differentiated 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Powrie" authorityYear="1870" box="[265,370,374,401]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="grandis">
<emphasis box="[265,281,375,400]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[296,370,374,400]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">grandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Powrie" authorityYear="1864" box="[439,570,374,401]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macnicoli">
<emphasis box="[439,455,375,400]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[471,570,374,400]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">macnicoli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the relative size of the fin spines, with the former having shorter fin spines relative to body size. However, the specimens 
<bibRefCitation author="POWRIE J." box="[267,417,469,495]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" pagination="284 - 301" refId="ref14807" refString="POWRIE J. 1870. - On the earliest known vestiges of vertebrate life; being a description of the fish remains of the Old Red Sandstone rocks of Forfarshire. Transactions of the Edinburgh Geological Society 1: 284 - 301." type="journal article" year="1870">Powrie (1870)</bibRefCitation>
assigned to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Powrie" authorityYear="1870" box="[545,647,469,496]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="grandis">
<emphasis box="[545,561,470,495]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[574,647,469,495]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">grandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
were much larger than the specimens he assigned to 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Powrie" authorityYear="1864" box="[144,273,533,559]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macnicoli">
<emphasis box="[144,160,533,558]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[175,273,533,559]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">macnicoli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Very few studies have been made in acanthodian species that compare the ratio of fin spine length to total length of the fish. As far as we can determine, 
<taxonomicName authority="Agassiz, 1833" authorityName="Agassiz" authorityYear="1833" box="[340,602,628,654]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acanthodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[340,453,628,654]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">Acanthodes</emphasis>
Agassiz, 1833
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authority="Upeniece, 1996" authorityName="Upeniece" authorityYear="1996" box="[113,432,659,685]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Lodeacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[113,252,659,685]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">Lodeacanthus</emphasis>
Upeniece, 1996
</taxonomicName>
are the only genera in which such work has been undertaken. 
<bibRefCitation author="ZIDEK J." pageId="5" pageNumber="326" pagination="1 - 41" refId="ref15491" refString="ZIDEK J. 1976. - Kansas Hamilton Quarry (Upper Pennsylvanian) Acanthodes, with remarks on the previously reported North American occurrences of the genus. The University of Kansas Paleontological Contributions Paper 83: 1 - 41." type="journal article" year="1976">Zidek (1976</bibRefCitation>
: table 2C-E; 1985: table 1d-g) showed that in 
<taxonomicName authority="Zidek, 1976" authorityName="Zidek" authorityYear="1976" box="[141,465,754,780]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acanthodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bridgei">
<emphasis box="[141,329,754,780]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">Acanthodes bridgei</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="ZIDEK J." box="[335,465,754,780]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" pagination="1 - 41" refId="ref15491" refString="ZIDEK J. 1976. - Kansas Hamilton Quarry (Upper Pennsylvanian) Acanthodes, with remarks on the previously reported North American occurrences of the genus. The University of Kansas Paleontological Contributions Paper 83: 1 - 41." type="journal article" year="1976">Zidek, 1976</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and also 
<taxonomicName authority="Zidek, 1980" authorityName="Zidek" authorityYear="1980" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acanthodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lundi">
<emphasis box="[562,647,754,781]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">A. lundi</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="ZIDEK J." box="[113,249,786,812]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" pagination="49 - 78" refId="ref15532" refString="ZIDEK J. 1980. - Acanthodes lundi, new species (Acanthodii), and associated coprolites from uppermost Mississippian Heath Formation of central Montana. Annals of the Carnegie Museum 49: 49 - 78." type="journal article" year="1980">Zidek, 1980</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
, the ratio of fin spine length to total specimen length showed no allometry, i.e. the ratio was approximately the same in fish of all sizes. In contrast, 
<bibRefCitation author="UPENIECE I." box="[249,427,881,907]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" pagination="1 - 221" refId="ref15038" refString="UPENIECE I. 2011. - Palaeoecology and juvenile individuals of the Devonian placoderm and acanthodian fishes from Lode site, Latvia. Disertations Geologicae Universitas Latviensis 21: 1 - 221." type="journal article" year="2011">Upeniece (2011</bibRefCitation>
: table 5.26) showed that relative fin spine lengths in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Upeniece" authorityYear="1996" box="[459,596,913,939]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Lodeacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[459,596,913,939]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">Lodeacanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
vary remarkably during ontogeny, but the variation between spine length and fish length appears random not allometric (
<bibRefCitation author="UPENIECE I." box="[275,439,1008,1034]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" pagination="1 - 221" refId="ref15038" refString="UPENIECE I. 2011. - Palaeoecology and juvenile individuals of the Devonian placoderm and acanthodian fishes from Lode site, Latvia. Disertations Geologicae Universitas Latviensis 21: 1 - 221." type="journal article" year="2011">Upeniece 2011</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 5.4). In at least some of the species of LORS acanthodians including 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Powrie" authorityYear="1864" box="[153,278,1071,1097]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macnicoli">
<emphasis box="[153,278,1071,1097]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">E. macnicoli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, the fin spines grew at a slower rate than the body, so that proportionally, larger specimens of a given species have smaller fin spines. This phenomenon was first recognised, as far as we know, by W. Graham-Smith (unpublished correspondence held in the Perth Museum and Art Gallery, 
<collectingCountry box="[545,637,1229,1256]" name="United Kingdom" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">Scotland</collectingCountry>
) and confirmed by the authors in many species. The allometric growth of the fin spines relative to body length in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Powrie" authorityYear="1864" box="[212,336,1325,1351]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macnicoli">
<emphasis box="[212,228,1325,1350]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[239,336,1325,1351]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">macnicoli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(using the posterior dorsal fin spine, which is most often the best preserved spine) is illustrated in 
<figureCitation box="[275,338,1388,1414]" captionStart="FIG" captionStartId="6.[113,124,710,728]" captionTargetBox="[219,1107,215,673]" captionTargetId="graphics-537@6.[292,1108,220,520]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIG. 2. — Euthacanthus macnicoli Powrie, 1864: comparison of length of fish compared with length of posterior dorsal fin spine, for 12 near complete specimens. Symbols: •, pdfs length (mm); ¢, fish length (mm)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4538459" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4538459/files/figure.png" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">Fig. 2</figureCitation>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[111,649,216,1700]" lastBlockId="5.[674,1211,216,590]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">
<bibRefCitation author="POWRIE J." box="[136,295,1420,1446]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" pagination="284 - 301" refId="ref14807" refString="POWRIE J. 1870. - On the earliest known vestiges of vertebrate life; being a description of the fish remains of the Old Red Sandstone rocks of Forfarshire. Transactions of the Edinburgh Geological Society 1: 284 - 301." type="journal article" year="1870">Powrie (1870)</bibRefCitation>
also differentiated between the two species by 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Powrie" authorityYear="1870" box="[276,378,1451,1478]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="grandis">
<emphasis box="[276,292,1452,1477]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[304,378,1451,1477]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">grandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
having larger scales with more grooves and ridges. Because acanthodian “onionskin-type growth” scales continued to increase in size while the fish itself grew (e.g., 
<bibRefCitation author="ZIDEK J." box="[511,640,1546,1572]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" pagination="1 - 41" refId="ref15491" refString="ZIDEK J. 1976. - Kansas Hamilton Quarry (Upper Pennsylvanian) Acanthodes, with remarks on the previously reported North American occurrences of the genus. The University of Kansas Paleontological Contributions Paper 83: 1 - 41." type="journal article" year="1976">Zidek 1976</bibRefCitation>
, 
<bibRefCitation author="ZIDEK J." box="[113,172,1578,1605]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" pagination="147 - 166" refId="ref15570" refString="ZIDEK J. 1985. - Growth in Acanthodes (Acanthodii: Pisces) data and implications. Palaontologische Zeitschrift 59: 147 - 166." type="journal article" year="1985">1985</bibRefCitation>
), it is hardly surprising to see larger scales in larger individuals. Like 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Agassiz" authorityYear="1833" box="[368,483,1610,1636]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acanthodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[368,483,1610,1636]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">Acanthodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fin spines, and unlike 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Powrie" authorityYear="1864" box="[189,330,1641,1667]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Chordata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[189,330,1641,1667]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">Euthacanthus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
fin spines, “scale size relative to the total specimen size is remarkably similar in most… 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Agassiz" authorityYear="1833" box="[769,887,216,242]" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Acanthodes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[769,887,216,242]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">Acanthodes</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species” (
<bibRefCitation author="ZIDEK J." box="[999,1196,216,243]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" pagination="147 - 166" refId="ref15570" refString="ZIDEK J. 1985. - Growth in Acanthodes (Acanthodii: Pisces) data and implications. Palaontologische Zeitschrift 59: 147 - 166." type="journal article" year="1985">Zidek 1985: 164</bibRefCitation>
). We consider 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Powrie" authorityYear="1870" box="[820,922,247,274]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="grandis">
<emphasis box="[820,836,248,273]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[848,922,247,273]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">grandis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
to be an advanced growth stage of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Powrie" authorityYear="1864" box="[762,890,279,306]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="macnicoli">
<emphasis box="[762,778,280,305]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">E</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[790,890,279,305]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">macnicoli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, and can recognize no specific differences between the two forms.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="5.[674,1211,216,590]" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">
The head and branchial region is not well preserved (if at all) in specimens of 
<emphasis box="[995,1211,374,400]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">
<taxonomicName box="[995,1207,374,400]" class="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" family="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" genus="Euthacanthus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Pisces (awaiting allocation)" pageId="5" pageNumber="326" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="gracilis">Euthacanthus gracilis</taxonomicName>
.
</emphasis>
However, NMS G.1891.92.243 (
<bibRefCitation author="NEWMAN M. J. &amp; DAVIDSON R. G. &amp; DEN BLAAUWEN J. L. &amp; BURROW C. J." pageId="5" pageNumber="326" pagination="101 - 111" refId="ref14554" refString="NEWMAN M. J., DAVIDSON R. G., DEN BLAAUWEN J. L. &amp; BURROW C. J. 2011. - The Early Devonian acanthodian Euthacanthus gracilis from the Midland Valley of Scotland. Scottish Journal of Geology 47: 101 - 111." type="journal article" year="2011">
Newman 
<emphasis box="[1156,1210,406,432]" italics="true" pageId="5" pageNumber="326">et al.</emphasis>
2011
</bibRefCitation>
: fig. 7A) shows several subparallel thick rods behind the jaws that are most likely to be branchiostegal plates; this specimen also has displaced sclerotic bones preserved above the jaws. We have thus revised the family diagnosis.
</paragraph>
